Abstract

We introduce Resonant Field Intelligence (RFI) , a novel framework in which cognition emerges as the self‑organization of continuous dynamical fields subject to topological, geometric, and physical constraints. Unlike conventional AI that relies on supervised learning from human‑labeled data, RFI defines intelligence as the convergence toward stable resonant attractors in a high‑dimensional state space, where truth is characterized by the vanishing of sheaf cohomology and falsehood corresponds to unstable patterns that naturally decay. We develop a rigorous mathematical foundation combining sheaf theory, symplectic geometry, and control theory. The cognitive field is modeled as a sheaf over a base space, and its evolution follows a reaction‑diffusion equation with a resonance operator that amplifies coherent local sections. Using LaSalle’s invariance principle, we prove that trajectories converge to global sections (truth states) under a Lyapunov function that penalizes incoherence. Equivariance under a Lie group yields conserved Noether currents, grounding the system in physical symmetries such as object permanence. The dynamics are discretized via a cellular sheaf and integrated with a symplectic Runge–Kutta–Munthe–Kaas method that exactly preserves invariants. Safety is enforced by a control barrier function that projects the dynamics onto a safe set, guaranteeing that the system never enters epistemically brittle regions. Persistent cohomology tracks the birth and death of hallucinations, and the spectral gap of the sheaf Laplacian quantifies the speed of thought and adversarial resilience. This work provides a complete, implementable blueprint for AI systems whose cognition is intrinsically aligned, physically grounded, and mathematically provable.

