2. Mathematical Foundations: Sheaves, Cohomology, and Laplacians

To formalize the notion of local consistency and global coherence, we adopt the language of sheaf theory. Sheaves provide a mathematical framework for gluing local data into global objects, and their cohomology measures obstructions to gluing.

2.1 Sheaves on a Site

Let \Omega be a topological space (or, more generally, a site). We consider the category \mathbf{Open}(\Omega) of open sets with inclusions. A presheaf \mathcal{F} of \mathbb{R}-vector spaces on \Omega assigns to each open set U a vector space \mathcal{F}(U) (the sections over U) and to each inclusion V \subset U a linear restriction map \rho_{U,V} : \mathcal{F}(U) \to \mathcal{F}(V) satisfying \rho_{U,U} = \mathrm{id} and \rho_{V,W} \circ \rho_{U,V} = \rho_{U,W} for W \subset V \subset U. A sheaf is a presheaf that satisfies the gluing axiom: for any open cover \{U_i\} of an open set U and any family of sections s_i \in \mathcal{F}(U_i) that agree on overlaps (s_i|_{U_i \cap U_j} = s_j|_{U_i \cap U_j}), there exists a unique section s \in \mathcal{F}(U) such that s|_{U_i} = s_i for all i.

In RFI, we view the base space \Omega as a latent manifold (e.g., a representation of sensorimotor states) and the sheaf \mathcal{F} as the cognitive substrate: each open set U corresponds to a collection of possible local “thoughts,” and the gluing axiom ensures that consistent local observations can be assembled into a global coherent representation.

2.2 Sheaf Cohomology and the Hallucination Theorem

The obstruction to gluing is captured by the first sheaf cohomology group H^1(\Omega, \mathcal{F}). For a finite open cover \mathcal{U} = \{U_i\}, Čech cohomology is defined via the cochain complex

0 \to C^0(\mathcal{U}, \mathcal{F}) \xrightarrow{\delta} C^1(\mathcal{U}, \mathcal{F}) \xrightarrow{\delta} C^2(\mathcal{U}, \mathcal{F}) \to \cdots,

where C^p(\mathcal{U}, \mathcal{F}) = \prod_{i_0,\dots,i_p} \mathcal{F}(U_{i_0}\cap\cdots\cap U_{i_p}) and \delta is the alternating difference. The cohomology groups H^p(\mathcal{U}, \mathcal{F}) are the cohomology of this complex; they are independent of the cover for sufficiently fine covers. In particular, H^1(\mathcal{U}, \mathcal{F}) classifies the failure of the gluing axiom: a family of local sections that agrees on overlaps gives a 1‑cocycle; it is a coboundary iff the family can be glued.

Definition 2.1 (Truth). A global configuration of the field \mathcal{F} (i.e., a global section S \in \mathcal{F}(\Omega)) is called a truth if it is obtained by gluing local sections. Equivalently, a configuration is a truth iff H^1(\Omega, \mathcal{F}) = 0.

Theorem 2.2 (Hallucination Theorem). A field configuration contains a hallucination (i.e., a local inconsistency that prevents global gluing) if and only if H^1(\Omega, \mathcal{F}) \neq 0.

Proof. By definition, H^1(\Omega, \mathcal{F}) \neq 0 means there exists a 1‑cocycle that is not a coboundary. Such a cocycle corresponds to a family of local sections that agree on overlaps but cannot be extended to a global section. Conversely, if the gluing axiom holds for all covers, then every 1‑cocycle is a coboundary, so H^1 = 0. ∎

This theorem is central to RFI: it provides a purely topological criterion for truth that does not rely on external labels. In practice, we will work with cellular sheaves on a finite discretization, where cohomology can be computed via linear algebra.

2.3 Cellular Sheaves and Sheaf Laplacian

For computational implementation, we discretize the base space as a finite cell complex (e.g., a graph). A cellular sheaf \mathcal{F} on a cell complex X assigns to each cell \sigma a vector space \mathcal{F}(\sigma) (the stalk), and to each face relation \sigma \subset \tau a linear map \mathcal{F}(\sigma \subset \tau): \mathcal{F}(\sigma) \to \mathcal{F}(\tau) (the restriction). The sheaf Laplacian L_{\mathcal{F}} is a linear operator on the space of 0‑cochains C^0(X, \mathcal{F}) = \bigoplus_{v \in V} \mathcal{F}(v). For a configuration \mathbf{x} = (x_v)_{v \in V}, the Laplacian is defined by

(L_{\mathcal{F}} \mathbf{x})_v = \sum_{u \sim v} \left( x_v - \rho_{uv}(x_u) \right),
\tag{2}

where the sum runs over neighboring vertices, and \rho_{uv} is the restriction map from u to v (if the sheaf is defined on a graph, we interpret each edge as a relation). The sheaf Laplacian is symmetric positive semidefinite with respect to the inner product \langle \mathbf{x}, \mathbf{y} \rangle = \sum_v \langle x_v, y_v \rangle if we require that the restriction maps are orthogonal and satisfy certain consistency conditions (see [Robinson, 2017] for details).

The coherence metric is then defined as

K(\mathbf{x}) = 1 - \frac{\mathbf{x}^T L_{\mathcal{F}} \mathbf{x}}{\|\mathbf{x}\|^2},
\tag{3}

which measures how close the configuration is to being harmonic (i.e., in the kernel of L_{\mathcal{F}}). Harmonic sections correspond precisely to global sections of the sheaf, and thus to truth states.

