5. Symmetries and Grounding via Noether’s Theorem

A key requirement for intelligent systems is that they respect the physical symmetries of the world, such as translation and rotation invariance (object permanence). In RFI, these symmetries are encoded via a Lie group action on the base space.

5.1 Equivariant Resonance

Let \mathcal{G} be a Lie group acting on the base space \Omega (e.g., SE(3) for rigid motions). We require the resonance operator to be \mathcal{G}-equivariant:

\mathcal{R}(g \cdot \mathcal{F}) = g \cdot \mathcal{R}(\mathcal{F}) \quad \forall g \in \mathcal{G}.
\tag{9}

In terms of the sheaf Laplacian, this means that the restriction maps \rho_{uv} are chosen to be compatible with the group action, i.e., the sheaf is \mathcal{G}-equivariant.

5.2 Noether’s Theorem and Conserved Currents

Because the dynamics (4) are Hamiltonian (see Section 6), the existence of a symmetry implies the conservation of a corresponding Noether current. For a Hamiltonian system with Hamiltonian H and symmetry group \mathcal{G}, each generator \xi of the Lie algebra \mathfrak{g} yields a conserved quantity J_\xi (the Noether charge). For the field theory (4), the conserved charges are given by

J_\xi = \int_\Omega \pi(x) \cdot (\xi \cdot \mathcal{F}(x)) \, dx,
\tag{10}

where \pi is the conjugate momentum (in the Hamiltonian formulation). These charges are constant along trajectories.

Theorem 5.1 (Grounding and Object Permanence). If the environment coupling \mathcal{E} is \mathcal{G}-invariant, then the Noether charges associated with \mathcal{G} are conserved. In particular, for the translation group, the total linear momentum is conserved; for rotations, angular momentum is conserved. Consequently, any stable attractor \mathcal{F}^* must be \mathcal{G}-invariant, and the system cannot spontaneously “forget” the position or orientation of objects without violating conservation laws. Hence, RFI inherently encodes object permanence and other physical symmetries.

Proof. Standard Noether theorem for Hamiltonian field theories. ∎

This result provides a mathematical proof that RFI’s knowledge is grounded in the physical structure of the world, rather than learned through statistical correlations.

