7. Multi‑Agent RFI

The framework naturally extends to multiple interacting agents. Let \{\mathcal{F}_i\} be fields associated with agents i = 1,\dots,N. The coupling is introduced via the environmental term \mathcal{E}:

\mathcal{E}_i(\mathcal{F}_i, t) = \sum_{j \neq i} \beta_{ij} (\mathcal{F}_j - \mathcal{F}_i) + \mathcal{E}_i^{\text{ext}}(t),
\tag{12}

where \beta_{ij} > 0 are coupling strengths. This diffusive coupling promotes synchronization: agents tend to align their fields.

The joint dynamics on the product manifold M^N can be analyzed using a Lyapunov function that includes pairwise disagreements. By LaSalle’s principle extended to product spaces, one can show that all agents converge to a common global section (consensus truth) provided the coupling graph is connected. This yields a model for collective intelligence without central coordination.

