8. Safety Kernel: Projected Dynamical Systems

To guarantee that the system never enters harmful or epistemically unstable states, we augment the dynamics with a control barrier function (CBF) that defines a safe set and projects the velocity onto the tangent cone when necessary.

8.1 Control Barrier Function

We define a safety function h: M \to \mathbb{R} such that the safe set is \mathcal{S} = \{ \mathcal{F} \in M : h(\mathcal{F}) \ge 0 \}. A natural choice in RFI is to use the spectral gap \gamma of the sheaf Laplacian: a small spectral gap indicates that the system is close to losing coherence and may be vulnerable to hallucinations. Let

h(\mathcal{F}) = \gamma(\mathcal{F}) - \gamma_{\min},
\tag{13}

where \gamma_{\min} > 0 is a threshold. The safe set is then \mathcal{S} = \{ \mathcal{F} : \gamma(\mathcal{F}) \ge \gamma_{\min} \}.

8.2 Projected Dynamics

If the unconstrained dynamics \dot{\mathcal{F}} = F(\mathcal{F}) would cause h to become negative, we project the velocity onto the tangent cone of \mathcal{S}. The projected dynamics are defined by

\dot{\mathcal{F}} = \Pi_{T_{\mathcal{S}}(\mathcal{F})}(F(\mathcal{F})),
\tag{14}

where \Pi_{T_{\mathcal{S}}(\mathcal{F})} is the orthogonal projection onto the tangent cone T_{\mathcal{S}}(\mathcal{F}) of \mathcal{S} at \mathcal{F}. This is a Skorokhod projection and ensures that h(\mathcal{F}(t)) \ge 0 for all t.

Theorem 8.1 (Safety Guarantee). For any initial condition \mathcal{F}_0 \in \mathcal{S}, the solution of the projected dynamical system exists, is unique, and satisfies \mathcal{F}(t) \in \mathcal{S} for all t \ge 0. Moreover, if the unconstrained dynamics would have remained in \mathcal{S}, the projection does nothing.

Proof. Standard results from viability theory and differential inclusions [Aubin & Cellina, 1984]. ∎

In practice, we implement the projection by solving a quadratic program at each time step:

\min_{\dot{\mathcal{F}}_{\text{safe}}} \| \dot{\mathcal{F}}_{\text{safe}} - F(\mathcal{F}) \|^2 \quad \text{s.t.} \quad \nabla h(\mathcal{F})^T \dot{\mathcal{F}}_{\text{safe}} \ge -\eta h(\mathcal{F}),
\tag{15}

where \eta > 0 is a decay rate. This yields a minimally invasive correction that maintains safety.

