9. Spectral Gap: Speed of Thought and Epistemic Resilience

The spectral gap \gamma of the sheaf Laplacian plays a central role in the cognitive properties of RFI. Let \lambda_1 \le \lambda_2 \le \dots be the eigenvalues of L_{\mathcal{F}}. The spectral gap is \gamma = \lambda_2 (the smallest positive eigenvalue), assuming the kernel corresponds to global sections.

9.1 Speed of Thought

Linearizing the dynamics around a truth state \mathcal{F}^* yields

\frac{\partial \delta \mathcal{F}}{\partial t} = -D L_{\mathcal{F}} \delta \mathcal{F} + \alpha \delta \mathcal{F} K(\mathcal{F}^*) + \dots .

Since K(\mathcal{F}^*) = 1 for a truth state, the linearized operator has eigenvalues -D \lambda_i + \alpha. The dominant eigenvalue (largest real part) is -D \gamma + \alpha. For stability, we require -D \gamma + \alpha < 0, i.e., \gamma > \alpha/D. The convergence rate is exponential with exponent \gamma' = D \gamma - \alpha. Thus, the speed of thought—the rate at which the system settles into a truth—is proportional to \gamma. A larger spectral gap yields faster convergence.

9.2 Epistemic Resilience

If an adversary injects a perturbation \xi into the field, the response in the direction of the eigenvector corresponding to \gamma decays as e^{-(D\gamma - \alpha)t}. Hence, a larger gap implies faster rejection of false information. This provides a quantifiable measure of epistemic resilience: the system with larger \gamma is more robust to adversarial noise.

Theorem 9.1 (Adversarial Robustness). Let \xi be a perturbation such that \|\xi\| \le \epsilon. The deviation from the truth attractor satisfies

\|\delta \mathcal{F}(t)\| \le \epsilon e^{-(D\gamma - \alpha)t}.
\tag{16}

Proof. Standard linear stability analysis. ∎

Thus, the spectral gap directly links the geometry of the cognitive space to the system’s cognitive performance and security.

