11. Expected Simulation Results

We anticipate the following qualitative behavior in the simulation:

· Phase I – Chaos: Initial random configuration yields low coherence K, small spectral gap \gamma, and many non‑zero cohomology classes (hallucinations). The system exhibits high spatial variation.
· Phase II – Nucleation: Under the influence of diffusion and resonance, small clusters of vertices become mutually consistent (satisfying x_v \approx M_{uv} x_u). Coherence begins to increase, the spectral gap widens, and some cohomology classes disappear.
· Phase III – Global Resonance: The field converges to a harmonic section, i.e., a global truth. Coherence approaches 1, the spectral gap stabilizes at a positive value, and all cohomology classes vanish. The system has “understood” the relational structure imposed by the restriction maps.

Adversarial test: Inject a perturbation designed to create a false local pattern that, if allowed to grow, would become a stable hallucination. With the safety kernel active, the system will reject the perturbation: the spectral gap will remain above the threshold, and the perturbation will decay. Without the kernel, the false pattern might persist or even dominate.

These results will be presented with plots of coherence, spectral gap, number of cohomology classes, and snapshots of the field over time.

