Appendix A: Sheaf Theory and Cohomology

This appendix provides a rigorous exposition of the sheaf-theoretic concepts used in the main thesis. We begin with the definition of sheaves on a topological space, then introduce Čech cohomology and cellular sheaves, and finally prove the Hallucination Theorem in full detail.

A.1 Sheaves on a Topological Space

Let X be a topological space. A presheaf \mathcal{F} of \mathbb{R}-vector spaces on X consists of:

· For each open set U \subset X, a vector space \mathcal{F}(U) (the sections over U);
· For each inclusion V \subset U, a linear map \rho_{U,V} : \mathcal{F}(U) \to \mathcal{F}(V) (the restriction map) such that \rho_{U,U} = \mathrm{id} and \rho_{V,W} \circ \rho_{U,V} = \rho_{U,W} for W \subset V \subset U.

A presheaf is a sheaf if it satisfies the gluing axiom: for any open cover \{U_i\}_{i \in I} of an open set U, and any family of sections s_i \in \mathcal{F}(U_i) such that s_i|_{U_i \cap U_j} = s_j|_{U_i \cap U_j} for all i,j, there exists a unique section s \in \mathcal{F}(U) with s|_{U_i} = s_i for all i.

A.2 Čech Cohomology

Fix an open cover \mathcal{U} = \{U_i\}_{i \in I} of X. For p \ge 0, define the space of p-cochains

C^p(\mathcal{U}, \mathcal{F}) = \prod_{i_0,\dots,i_p} \mathcal{F}(U_{i_0} \cap \cdots \cap U_{i_p}),

with the convention that the product is over all ordered (p+1)-tuples. The coboundary operator \delta : C^p \to C^{p+1} is given by

(\delta s)_{i_0,\dots,i_{p+1}} = \sum_{k=0}^{p+1} (-1)^k s_{i_0,\dots,\hat{i}_k,\dots,i_{p+1}}|_{U_{i_0}\cap\cdots\cap U_{i_{p+1}}}.

One checks that \delta \circ \delta = 0. The cohomology groups are defined as

H^p(\mathcal{U}, \mathcal{F}) = \ker(\delta : C^p \to C^{p+1}) / \operatorname{im}(\delta : C^{p-1} \to C^p).

For a sheaf, the cohomology groups are independent of the cover when taking the direct limit over refinements; we denote the resulting groups by H^p(X, \mathcal{F}).

A.3 The Hallucination Theorem

Theorem A.1 (Hallucination Theorem). A configuration (global section) S \in \mathcal{F}(X) exists if and only if H^1(X, \mathcal{F}) = 0. Moreover, if H^1(X, \mathcal{F}) \neq 0, there exists a family of local sections that agree on overlaps but cannot be glued to a global section; such a family is a hallucination.

Proof. The sheaf condition is exactly that the map C^0 \to C^1 is injective and that every compatible family gives a global section. In Čech cohomology, H^1 = 0 means that every 1-cocycle is a coboundary. A 1-cocycle corresponds to a family of sections on overlaps satisfying the cocycle condition; it is a coboundary iff it comes from a 0-cochain, i.e., a global section. Hence H^1 = 0 is equivalent to the gluing property. ∎

For a cellular sheaf on a finite cell complex, the cohomology can be computed via the cellular cochain complex, and the condition H^1 = 0 becomes a linear algebra condition.

A.4 Cellular Sheaves

Let X be a finite cell complex. A cellular sheaf \mathcal{F} assigns:

· To each cell \sigma (vertex, edge, etc.) a vector space \mathcal{F}(\sigma);
· To each face relation \sigma \subset \tau a linear map \mathcal{F}(\sigma \subset \tau) : \mathcal{F}(\sigma) \to \mathcal{F}(\tau) such that composition is identity for equal cells and consistent for chains of inclusions.

The cochain complex is built from the stalks on cells. For vertices v, we have C^0 = \bigoplus_v \mathcal{F}(v); for edges e = \{u,v\}, we have C^1 = \bigoplus_e \mathcal{F}(e) (with orientation). The coboundary \delta_0 : C^0 \to C^1 is given by

(\delta_0 s)_e = \mathcal{F}(u \subset e)(s_u) - \mathcal{F}(v \subset e)(s_v),

with appropriate signs depending on orientation. The sheaf Laplacian is then L = \delta_0^* \delta_0 (using inner products on stalks), and its kernel is isomorphic to H^0. The condition H^1 = 0 is equivalent to the surjectivity of \delta_0 onto the orthogonal complement of \ker \delta_0^*.

