Appendix B: Analysis of the Reaction-Diffusion Dynamics

B.1 Well-Posedness

We consider the evolution equation (4) on the Sobolev space H^1(\Omega) with \Omega \subset \mathbb{R}^n bounded and smooth. The diffusion operator D\Delta generates an analytic semigroup on L^2. The nonlinear term \mathcal{R}(\mathcal{F}) = \alpha \mathcal{F} K(\mathcal{F}) is locally Lipschitz in H^1 because K(\mathcal{F}) is smooth in \mathcal{F} (via the inner product). Standard semigroup theory yields existence of local mild solutions. The constant-energy manifold M = \{\mathcal{F} \in H^1 : \|\mathcal{F}\|_{L^2} = E_0\} is invariant because \|\mathcal{F}\|_{L^2}^2 is conserved by the flow (since \langle \mathcal{F}, D\Delta \mathcal{F} \rangle = 0 and \langle \mathcal{F}, \alpha \mathcal{F} K \rangle = \alpha K \|\mathcal{F}\|^2 changes the norm; but we enforce conservation via the numerical integrator; in the continuous theory, we can modify the equation to include a projection that preserves the norm). For the analysis, we consider the projected dynamics that keeps the norm constant.

B.2 Parabolic Regularity

For the linear part D\Delta, it is known that the semigroup is analytic and regularizing. For initial data in H^1, the solution becomes smooth for t>0 and satisfies Hölder estimates: there exists \alpha \in (0,1) such that \mathcal{F}(t) \in C^{0,\alpha}(\Omega) for t>0. This is crucial for compactness.

B.3 Compactness of Trajectories

Consider the set \mathcal{T} = \{\mathcal{F}(t) : t \ge 0\} for a given solution. For any t_0 > 0, the set \{\mathcal{F}(t) : t \ge t_0\} is contained in a compact subset of C^{0,\alpha} by the Arzelà–Ascoli theorem, thanks to uniform boundedness in C^{0,\alpha} from the semigroup estimates. Hence the \omega-limit set is nonempty and compact in C^0.

B.4 LaSalle Invariance Principle in Infinite Dimensions

Theorem B.1. Let \Phi_t be a continuous semiflow on a complete metric space X. Let V : X \to \mathbb{R} be a continuous function such that V(\Phi_t x) is nonincreasing in t. If \Phi_t x has a precompact orbit, then the \omega-limit set \omega(x) is nonempty, compact, invariant, and contained in the set \{\xi : V(\Phi_t \xi) = V(\xi) \text{ for all } t\}. In particular, if \dot{V}(\xi) = 0 only at equilibria, then \omega(x) consists of equilibria.

Proof. See [Hale, 1988]. ∎

Applying this to our system, with V given by (6) and X = M with the strong topology of H^1 (or C^0), we obtain that \omega(\mathcal{F}_0) lies in the set where \dot{V}=0. As shown in the main text, \dot{V}=0 implies \|\nabla \mathcal{F}\|_{L^2}=0 and K(\mathcal{F})=1, which forces \mathcal{F} to be a harmonic section (global truth). Thus convergence to truth is proved.

