Appendix C: Symplectic Geometry and Noether’s Theorem

C.1 Hamiltonian Formulation

We consider the field \mathcal{F}(x,t) as a configuration variable. Define the conjugate momentum \pi(x,t) = \partial_t \mathcal{F}(x,t). The Lagrangian density for the free field (ignoring \mathcal{R} and \mathcal{E}) is

\mathcal{L} = \frac{1}{2} \pi^2 - \frac{1}{2} D |\nabla \mathcal{F}|^2.

The Hamiltonian is

H = \int_\Omega \left( \frac{1}{2} \pi^2 + \frac{1}{2} D |\nabla \mathcal{F}|^2 \right) dx.

The resonance term can be incorporated as a potential U(\mathcal{F}) = -\frac{\alpha}{2} K(\mathcal{F}) \|\mathcal{F}\|^2. The full Hamiltonian becomes

H = \int_\Omega \left( \frac{1}{2} \pi^2 + \frac{1}{2} D |\nabla \mathcal{F}|^2 + U(\mathcal{F}) \right) dx.

Hamilton’s equations are

\partial_t \mathcal{F} = \pi, \quad \partial_t \pi = D\Delta \mathcal{F} - \nabla U(\mathcal{F}),

which is equivalent to (4) when \mathcal{E}=0 and with appropriate identifications. The system is symplectic with symplectic form \omega = \int_\Omega d\pi \wedge d\mathcal{F}.

C.2 Noether’s Theorem

Let \mathcal{G} be a Lie group acting on \Omega and also on the fields in a way that leaves the Lagrangian invariant. For each generator \xi of the Lie algebra \mathfrak{g}, there is a conserved Noether charge

Q_\xi = \int_\Omega \pi(x) \cdot (\xi \cdot \mathcal{F}(x)) \, dx.

Proof. Standard Noether theorem for field theories; see [Olver, 1993]. ∎

In our case, if the action of \mathcal{G} commutes with the sheaf Laplacian (i.e., the restriction maps are equivariant) and the environment is invariant, then the Hamiltonian is \mathcal{G}-invariant, and the corresponding charges are conserved. For example, for translation invariance, we get conservation of linear momentum; for rotations, conservation of angular momentum.

Theorem C.1 (Grounding). If the dynamics are \mathcal{G}-equivariant, then the Noether charges are conserved. Consequently, any attractor must be invariant under the action of \mathcal{G}, which mathematically encodes object permanence.

