Appendix D: Geometric Integration – RKMK Method

D.1 Lie Group Integrators

We consider a Hamiltonian system on a symplectic manifold that is a Lie group G (or a homogeneous space). The RKMK method is defined as follows:

Given a step size h, for stage i=1,\dots,s:

k_i = F\left( g_n \exp\left( h \sum_{j=1}^{s} a_{ij} k_j \right) \right),

where F is the vector field lifted to the Lie algebra via the exponential map. The update is

g_{n+1} = g_n \exp\left( h \sum_{i=1}^s b_i k_i \right).

The coefficients (a_{ij}, b_i) are chosen to satisfy the symplectic condition; for instance, the Gauss–Legendre methods are symplectic and have high order.

For quadratic Hamiltonians, the vector field is linear, and the exponential map can be computed exactly. More generally, we can use a splitting method: split the Hamiltonian into exactly solvable parts (e.g., kinetic and potential) and compose symplectic steps.

D.2 Error Analysis

Symplectic integrators preserve the symplectic form exactly and have a global error that grows linearly in time, rather than exponentially. This is essential for long-term simulations.

Theorem D.1. For a symplectic integrator of order p, the global error after N steps of size h satisfies

\|g_N - \Phi_{Nh}(g_0)\| \le C h^p (Nh) = C h^{p-1} T,

for T = Nh fixed, where C depends on the smoothness of the Hamiltonian.

Proof. See [Hairer, Lubich, & Wanner, 2006]. ∎

Thus, even for very long times, the error remains bounded linearly in T.

