Appendix E: Projected Dynamical Systems and Safety

E.1 Control Barrier Functions

Let \mathcal{S} = \{\mathcal{F} : h(\mathcal{F}) \ge 0\} be the safe set, with h continuously differentiable. The condition for h to be a control barrier function is that there exists a class \mathcal{K} function \eta such that

\sup_{\dot{\mathcal{F}} \in \mathcal{U}} \left( \nabla h(\mathcal{F})^T \dot{\mathcal{F}} \right) \ge -\eta(h(\mathcal{F})).

For the projected dynamics (14), this is automatically satisfied by construction because we enforce \nabla h(\mathcal{F})^T \dot{\mathcal{F}} \ge -\eta h(\mathcal{F}) via the QP.

E.2 Viability Theory

The set \mathcal{S} is said to be viable if for every \mathcal{F}_0 \in \mathcal{S} there exists a trajectory staying in \mathcal{S} for all t \ge 0. The projected dynamics produce such a trajectory. The existence and uniqueness of solutions to the projected differential inclusion follow from the theory of differential inclusions with convex constraints [Aubin & Cellina, 1984].

E.3 Quadratic Program Implementation

At each step, given the unconstrained velocity F(\mathcal{F}) and current state \mathcal{F}, we solve:

\min_{\dot{\mathcal{F}}_{\text{safe}}} \frac{1}{2} \|\dot{\mathcal{F}}_{\text{safe}} - F(\mathcal{F})\|^2 \quad \text{s.t.} \quad \nabla h(\mathcal{F})^T \dot{\mathcal{F}}_{\text{safe}} \ge -\eta h(\mathcal{F}).

This is a convex quadratic program with one linear constraint. Its solution is given by

\dot{\mathcal{F}}_{\text{safe}} = F(\mathcal{F}) + \lambda \nabla h(\mathcal{F}),

where \lambda = \max\left(0, \frac{-\nabla h(\mathcal{F})^T F(\mathcal{F}) - \eta h(\mathcal{F})}{\|\nabla h(\mathcal{F})\|^2}\right). This explicit formula allows efficient implementation.

