Appendix F: Spectral Theory of the Sheaf Laplacian

F.1 Definition and Basic Properties

For a cellular sheaf on a graph, the sheaf Laplacian L_{\mathcal{F}} is a symmetric positive semidefinite matrix of size \sum_v \dim \mathcal{F}(v). Its kernel corresponds to global sections (harmonic sections). The eigenvalues are nonnegative, and we denote them by 0 = \lambda_1 \le \lambda_2 \le \cdots \le \lambda_N. The spectral gap is \gamma = \lambda_2 if the kernel is exactly the space of global sections (which we assume for connected sheaves with trivial holonomy).

F.2 Relation to Graph Laplacian

If all restriction maps are identities and the stalks are 1-dimensional, then L_{\mathcal{F}} reduces to the graph Laplacian, and \gamma is the algebraic connectivity (Fiedler eigenvalue). In general, the sheaf Laplacian can be seen as a block version, and its eigenvalues satisfy interlacing inequalities with the graph Laplacian under certain conditions.

F.3 Computation

For moderate-sized graphs, we can compute the full spectrum via standard linear algebra libraries (e.g., LAPACK). For large graphs, we can use iterative methods like Lanczos or Arnoldi to estimate the smallest positive eigenvalue. The spectral gap can also be approximated using the power method on the inverse or by solving the generalized eigenvalue problem.

F.4 Spectral Gap and Persistence

The number of zero eigenvalues equals the dimension of H^0. When H^1 \neq 0, there exist additional zero eigenvalues (or near-zero) in the spectrum? In fact, the first Betti number (dimension of H^1) is related to the number of zero eigenvalues of the edge Laplacian. For our purpose, the spectral gap \gamma is the smallest positive eigenvalue of L_{\mathcal{F}}. A small \gamma indicates that the sheaf is nearly not globally coherent, which correlates with non-zero H^1.

